https://us3.campaign-archive.com/?u=88247005ecfbacf91efa65685&id=257434e00d,Image source: Instagram The stream of misinformation surrounding 5G technology and the coronavirus has prompted Australia's chief medical officer, Brendan Murphy, to address the issue. Speaking at a recent press briefing, Dr Murphy said there was "absolutely no evidence about 5G doing anything in the coronavirus space".
"I have unfortunately received a lot of communication from these conspiracy theorists myself," he said. "It is complete nonsense."
In the UK, a partnership between Twitter and the government means users searching for 5G conspiracy tweets will see a pop-up informing them that "the UK government has said there is no evidence of a link between 5G and coronavirus (COVID-19)" and directing them to further information.
In one recent example of 5G misinformation, a video that has been viewed thousands of times shows a supposed telecoms engineer who is erecting 5G masts in the UK holding up an electrical circuit board. The man claims the board is "a piece of kit that has COV-19 on it".Reuters found that the circuit board was not used in 5G technology but that it had been taken from a Virgin Media box for cable television. Virgin Media told Reuters the board was from a "very old set-top box" and had never been inscribed or imprinted with "COV-19".
"It has absolutely no relation with any mobile network infrastructure, including that used for 5G."
Similarly, a claim that "radiation pneumonitis" allegedly caused by 5G was being misdiagnosed as COVID-19 was also found to be false by Reuters. Remdesivir is the latest drug being hailed as a promising treatment for COVID-19. But how accurate are claims about patents, ownership and profits related to the drug?
Firstly, remdesivir is an experimental antiviral drug, manufactured by pharmaceutical company Gilead and recently approved as a COVID-19 treatment in the US. In Australia, the drug is not yet being used in any clinical trials, though some hospitals are expected to receive doses of the drug for use with COVID-19 patients. Misinformation around COVID-19 treatments, including remdesivir, have spread rapidly throughout the pandemic.
In one example, a Facebook post claimed that hydroxychloroquine, another touted COVID-19 treatment, was "91 per cent effective" and cheap, while remdesivir was effective in just 50 per cent of patients and cost US$1,000.
"Why is Fauci pushing Remdesivir? It was invented by Fauci and Gates. Its stock is now soaring. Always follow the $$$$$$$." the post stated, referencing US infectious diseases expert and White House adviser Anthony Fauci and Microsoft founder Bill Gates.
But USA Today found that neither hydroxychloroquine nor remdesivir had been proven effective against COVID-19, with clinical trials ongoing. Further, Gilead Sciences was the only organisation able to profit from the sale of remdesivir and neither Mr Gates nor Dr Fauci had any involvement in the development of the drug. 
Another Facebook post imagines a remdesivir conspiracy centred around Unitaid, which it suggests is Gilead's "drug patent sharing subsidiary branch". Unitaid apparently has an office in Wuhan, and is backed by Bill and Melinda Gates, billionaire investor George Soros and the World Health Organisation. Hillary Clinton, Dr Fauci and Wuhan’s Institute of Virology also rate mentions. Snopes found these claims to be false. Unitaid is not linked to Gilead and does not have an office near Wuhan. And while the organisation, which invests in innovations to prevent, diagnose and treat a number of global health issues, is supported financially by the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, it has no ties to Mr Soros or Dr Fauci. Unitaid is a "hosted partnership" of the WHO, but receives no financial support from the organisation. A number of news stories in recent days have raised concerns that COVID-19, which has been viewed mainly as a respiratory disease, may also be killing sufferers through thrombosis (the formation of blood clots).
UK-based Full Fact took a look at claims posted on social media that COVID-19 patients were being misdiagnosed with pneumonia, when really they were suffering from thrombosis. The posts went on to say that the way to fight the disease is with "antibiotics, antivirals, anti-inflammatories and anticoagulants".
The fact checkers found that patients were not being "misdiagnosed" with pneumonia. Rather, both pneumonia and Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation (DIC), which leads to thrombosis, had been found to be present in COVID-19 cases.
Indian-based BOOM also found that, contrary to some claims, respiratory failure rather than thrombosis was the leading cause of COVID-19 deaths.
"It is thought that thrombosis of the lungs is a factor that can further complicate the course of pneumonia in COVID-19 patients," they said.
When it came to how to treat COVID-19, Full Fact found that antibiotics were not recommended, given they are used to treat bacterial infections rather than viruses like COVID-19. And while antivirals can be used to treat viral infections, no specific drug has been shown conclusively to be effective against COVID-19.
Meanwhile, anti-inflammatories such as ibuprofen could be helpful in treating COVID-19 symptoms at home, and there was evidence to suggest anticoagulants helped treat some patients. With little else to keep them occupied, many Australians are turning to exercise in order to relieve boredom and stay fit and healthy during the coronavirus restrictions.Claims made online, however, have suggested that exercise may actually weaken the immune system. In one example, an advertisement linking to an article claims that a "window of opportunity" exists in the hours after strenuous exercise which can leave people vulnerable to infection from viruses.
Fact checkers at USA Today found that the "window of opportunity" theory has been around for decades, supported by at least one study that found "vigorous workouts could have a temporary negative effect on the immune system".
But when it came to the long-term effects of exercising, several scientific studies suggested regular exercise promotes good health and reduces the risk of infections.
"People should not fear that their immune system will be suppressed by exercise, placing them at increased risk of coronavirus," John Campbell, of the University of Bath's Department of Health, told USA Today. #26: Brown sugar"There is no official cure for COVID-19 as of May 21, according to the World Health Organization (WHO). There are several clinical trials being conducted to test potential cures, but consuming brown sugar is not one of them."
- Rappler As the US grapples with soaring numbers of COVID-19 cases and the highest number of deaths in the world, Republicans are blaming former Democratic president Barack Obama for having left the current administration poorly placed to cope with the pandemic.
During an online discussion hosted by President Trump’s re-election campaign, Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell said it may no longer be that pandemics are a once-in-100-year occurrence, and he wanted to be ready for the next one.
"Clearly, the Obama administration did not leave to this administration any kind of game plan for something like this."
But fact checkers at the Washington Post, CNN’s Fact First and Politifact found that claim to be false, and that the Obama administration had left behind a 40-page National Security Council "playbook" on fighting pandemics.
"McConnell is wrong to say the Obama administration left "no game plan" to deal with a pandemic," the Washington Post concluded.
"The Obama team crafted a detailed document setting forth questions and policies that should be considered, as well as put in place programs that might have helped spur action sooner."
Senator McConnell later conceded in a Fox News interview: "I was wrong." Australia has seen an "unprecedented" drop in the number of hours worked, according to the Australian Bureau of Statistics, plunging 9.2 per cent between March and April.
Women were more adversely affected by the drop in hours (down 11.5 per cent), compared to men (down 7.5 per cent).,
https://us3.campaign-archive.com/?u=88247005ecfbacf91efa65685&id=43a7ff5f04,Image source:  ABC News - Nick. Haggarty Touted by some as a miracle cure for COVID-19, the anti-malarial drug hydroxychloroquine was thrust into the spotlight again this week when US President Donald Trump revealed he was taking it to avoid contracting the illness. 
The drug recently made headlines in Australia when outspoken businessman Clive Palmer donated almost 33 million doses — reportedly more than the equivalent of entire US stocks — to Australia’s national medical stockpile. In a series of newspaper ads and TV interviews, Mr Palmer claimed hydroxychloroquine was behind Australia’s low mortality rate, which he said had fallen since the drug was made available to treat hospitalised coronavirus patients in early April.
But can Australia’s success be linked to the drug? Fact Check asked the experts and found Mr Palmer’s claim to be baseless. In fact, the drug was already available to hospital patients, and experts said the death curve had flattened because just a few weeks earlier the case curve had done the same.
The jury is still out on whether the drug works as a treatment for COVID-19. However, the evidence isn't promising. Given the known risks of hydroxychloroquine, Australia's medicines regulatory body strongly advises against giving it to coronavirus patients in the absence of positive clinical trial results. It feels like ancient history, but for a time, just a few short weeks ago, supermarket shelves normally filled with toilet paper, pasta, flour and cleaning supplies were bare and the Prime Minister labelled the apparent cause, panic buying, "ridiculous" and "not sensible".
Despite those scenes, federal Agriculture Minister David Littleproud recently declared that Australia had "the most secure food security in the world".
"We're a nation of 25 million people," Mr Littleproud told ABC Radio National's Afternoon Briefing program on May 11. "We produce enough food for 75 million."
In a fact check published earlier this week, we found that claim to be in the ballpark.
Many studies and experts say Australia enjoys a very high level of food security, exports far more than it needs and has ample alternative sources of certain foods should they become scarce.
In terms of Australia's international ranking, we're not quite the most food secure nation but one comparison places us 12th among 113 countries in terms of food security. A post shared widely on Facebook and attributed to the Department of Health claims that tests for the novel coronavirus, known as SARS-COV-2, are not able to distinguish the virus from other illnesses.
"It should be noted that PCR tests cannot distinguish between "live" virus and non-infective RNA," the post states. "This means the test cannot [distinguish] covid from a cold or measles or ebola."
  As Australian Medical Association ACT President Antonio Di Dio explained to the ABC in March, Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR) tests are the most widely used COVID-19 tests in Australia, and work by taking a "fingerprint" of RNA from a patient. 
"In the context of COVID-19, you get a piece of the RNA from a swab of the patient, you double it, then again and again," Dr Di Dio said. "Until you have millions of copies." Within a few hours, the sample would be large enough to see whether COVID-19 is present.
A caption alongside the Facebook post claims the information has been taken "from [the Department of Health’s] own website".
In a statement, a department spokesman told RMIT ABC Fact Check the post contained "selectively chosen information taken out of context" from a factsheet for clinicians, along with "complete inaccuracies".
"The factsheet is actually dealing with COVID-19 positive people continuing to test positive after the infectious period has passed," the spokesman said. "It is true that the PCR may still result in a positive test, because of remaining non-infectious viral load within the patient."
He said the test would not detect any pathogen other than the SARS-COV-2 virus. Image source: Twitter/@DeepStateExpose NewsGuard, a self-described "internet trust tool", has published a list of Twitter "super spreaders" — accounts that "repeat, share and amplify" coronavirus misinformation and myths to large numbers of followers.
The 10 accounts listed by NewsGuard reach a combined 3.3 million followers and have continued to publish misinformation despite Twitter announcing a crackdown on March 18 in a bid to address the so-called "infodemic".
Included in the list are the accounts of former Nigerian politician Femi Fani-Kayode, conservative radio commentator Bill Mitchell and former British footballer David Icke.
The accounts have propagated myths including that COVID-19 does not exist and that zinc or herbal remedies can prevent or cure the virus, and are spreading unproven claims about the effect of 5G technology on the virus. #25: A vegetarian diet "No evidence exists to support the claim that a vegetarian lifestyle can protect someone from contracting COVID-19, a claim that has been debunked by media outlets and the Indian government." - Snopes US President Donald Trump this week claimed that he had been taking hydroxychloroquine as a COVID-19 preventative, prompting scorn from political adversaries including House of Representatives Speaker Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat.
"He's our president, and I would rather he not be taking something that has not been approved by the scientists, especially in his age group and, shall we say, his weight group, [which] is morbidly obese, they say," Ms Pelosi told CNN.
While her comments were met with glee by some, others have accused her of "fat shaming". But was her comment accurate? 
Not quite, according to fact checkers at PolitiFact, who found that based on figures from Mr Trump's latest physical examination he would not be considered "morbidly obese" by medical standards. Weighing in at 243 pounds (110 kilograms) and measuring 6 feet 3 inches (191 centimetres), Mr Trump just falls into the obese category.
And while some pundits have questioned the official height and weight figures provided by Mr Trump, PolitiFact found that he would need to be shorter than 5 feet 8 inches (173 centimetres) and weigh 260 pounds (118 kilograms) to be classified "morbidly obese". Australia has recorded its biggest-ever drop in overseas visitor numbers, with arrivals falling 60 per cent year-on-year in March.
The figures, issued by the Australian Bureau of Statistics, also reveal a record decline in the number of Australians returning from short-term (less than one year) trips overseas.,
https://us3.campaign-archive.com/?u=88247005ecfbacf91efa65685&id=0987e8c850,Image source: Facebook A Facebook post shared in the US, Canada and Australia providing advice on “how to legally decline a vaccine” has been debunked by fact checkers at AFP and Lead Stories.
The post suggests people should ask questions including whether a vaccine (and presumably any potential COVID-19 vaccine) contains "MRC-5" and whether it may result in an "iatrogenic reaction". If the doctor administering the vaccine answers in the affirmative, ,then a person apparently has the right to decline.
"Remember, doctors have sworn the Hippocratic Oath (which is to do no harm) and they MUST honour it,” the post states. “This is how we can legally (and respectfully) decline their offered mandated services and there is absolutely NOTHING they can do about it!"
But AFP found that while there were ways to refuse a vaccine legally in each of the jurisdictions in which the post has been circulating, they were not those listed.
While some Australian states mandate vaccinations for children enrolling in childcare or school, vaccination itself is not compulsory so the steps outlined in the post for refusing a vaccine did not apply. 
"While the government supports immunisation, it is not compulsory and people maintain the right to choose whether to receive a vaccination," a spokesperson for the Department of Health told AFP. Image source: News Break NG One of the first recipients of a trial vaccine for COVID-19 has been the subject of false reports of her death, Full Fact and Reuters have found.
Elisa Granato, who is part of a vaccine trial at the University of Oxford, and is herself a scientist, was reported to have died shortly after receiving the vaccine last week.
However, there was no truth to the reports. Dr Granato tweeted at the weekend that she was "doing fine" while the university issued a statement in response to a Reuters’ query confirming that she was "alive and well". The UK Department of Health and Social Care also tweeted that the news was "completely untrue".
Dr Granato is among 800 participants who will either receive the trial vaccine or a control vaccine as part of the study.  Australians have been warned to be on the lookout for digital scammers using the coronavirus pandemic to con them into buying goods, sharing personal information and installing malicious software on their computers.  Image source: Twitter A little while ago we brought you a story about celebrity chef Pete Evans and his "hybrid subtle energy revitalisation platform", a light-emitting device he implied could help cure or treat COVID-19.
Since then, the Therapeutic Goods Administration (TGA) has fined Mr Evans $25,200.In a statement, the administration found claims that the so-called BioCharger could be used in relation to what Mr Evans referred to as the "Wuhan Coronavirus" had "no apparent foundation".
"Any claim that references COVID-19 is a restricted representation under therapeutic goods legislation, and is of significant concern to the TGA given the heightened public concern about the pandemic.” Image source: YouTube: Fox News Comparisons between the coronavirus and various causes of death have been rife as some commentators, politicians and business owners push for economies to reopen and for a return to business-as-usual. One such comparison was made by TV’s "Dr Phil" — real name Phil McGraw — who claimed during a Fox News interview that 45,000 Americans die every year in road accidents, 480,000 from smoking and 360,000 in swimming pools.As PolitiFact found, while Dr Phil had the ballpark figures correct for smoking and road deaths, he overstated the number of people who die by drowning each year in the US by almost 10 times the actual figure.
In reality, 3,709 drowned in 2017, including those people who drowned in natural bodies of water and baths, not just swimming pools. 
Regardless, PolitiFact warns against apples-and-oranges comparisons, quoting Arthur Caplan, the founding head of the division of medical ethics at the New York University School of Medicine.
"The issue isn’t how many people die of car crashes or swimming pool accidents or strokes or whatever,” Caplan said. "The question is whether they all happen at once and overwhelm the healthcare system." #18: A few drops of hydrogen peroxide in the ear canal  “This does not sound plausible. Liquids won't penetrate the eardrum. In fact, it seals off the middle ear and prevents that from happening. Some drugs can be absorbed through the skin, but hydrogen peroxide is not one of them.” - Dr Mark Prince, quoted by Lead Stories Regular readers of this newsletter can probably guess the likely subject of this section today: the extraordinary potential COVID-19 treatments floated by US President Donald Trump in recent days.
During what now appears to have been one of his final daily coronavirus press briefings last week, Mr Trump pondered whether disinfectant could be injected into the body to kill off the virus, or whether "very powerful" light could be a potential treatment.PolitiFact found "no evidence that using sunlight or disinfectants could help treat COVID-19 patients".
On the suggestion that light therapy could kill the virus, Dr Jonathan Reiner, a cardiologist at The George Washington University Hospital, told CNN’s Facts First: "Very little of what the President said as it pertains to disinfection or phototherapy makes any sense."
Meanwhile, the company that owns disinfectant brands Dettol and Lysol issued a statement which reads: "As a global leader in health and hygiene products, we must be clear that under no circumstance should our disinfectant products be administered into the human body (through injection, ingestion or any other route)."
But that wasn’t the end of it for our fact-checking colleagues in the US — Mr Trump later claimed his comments had amounted to sarcasm. CNN Facts First branded that claim a lie, while factcheck.org simply presented the videos of Mr Trump's comments and invited readers to make up their own minds. Reporters at the New York Times and Financial Times have found that the true death toll of COVID-19 may be far higher than official numbers.
By comparing the number of deaths this year to historical averages, the investigators show that the extra deaths recorded since the outbreak of the virus actually exceed the official coronavirus death tolls reported in most of the countries studied.
This graph, from the Financial Times, shows deaths in the province of Guayas, in Ecuador, were more than 10,000 above the average, though just 245 official COVID-19 deaths were recorded between March 1 and April 15.,
https://us3.campaign-archive.com/?u=88247005ecfbacf91efa65685&id=0e85eb9fcf,Image source: Twitter Author of the uber-successful Harry Potter franchise JK Rowling last week announced she’d had "all the symptoms" of the coronavirus but had since recovered, in part thanks to the help of a breathing technique seen performed in a video by a doctor from Queen's Hospital, London.
But the technique, a type of controlled coughing, has been called into question in an article published by The Conversation, which said it could actually help spread the virus.
According to Brian Oliver, the head of the respiratory molecular pathogenesis group at the University of Technology Sydney, coughing as instructed in the video could directly infect people close by or spread the virus by transferring it to hands and surfaces.
"One common COVID-19 symptom is a dry cough," Professor Oliver added. "So, it’s difficult to imagine why controlled coughing would help when you’re coughing so much anyway."
Full Fact in the UK also examined  the video and quoted the Association of Chartered Physiotherapists and Respiratory Care, which said: "If you have the symptoms of coronavirus and do have a persistent dry cough, there is no reason to make yourself cough after taking deep breaths." Image source: ABC News It was only a matter of time before Pete Evans (celebrity chef, champion of alternative medicines and fan-activated almonds) spruiked a bogus coronavirus treatment.
'Paleo Pete' used an Instagram live video last week to promote the BioCharger NG, which is described on his website as a “hybrid subtle energy revitalisation platform” in which "four transmitted energies stimulate and invigorate the entire body to optimise and improve potential health, wellness, and athletic performance".
In the video, Mr Evans claimed the product was programmed with a thousand different "recipes" including some for the novel coronavirus. What that means exactly is unclear, but it would certainly appear to imply the machine could help treat or prevent COVID-19.
But, according to the ABC, the makers of the device were quick to distance themselves from Mr Evans’s comments, stating: "The BioCharger is not a medical device."
The Australian Medical Association also lambasted Mr Evans in a tweet, calling the device a "$15,000 fancy light machine" and pointing to the celebrity chef’s lack of scientific and medical qualifications. With shortages worldwide of personal protection equipment, many people are attempting to find ways to reuse protective face masks. A suggestion that the masks should be microwaved in order to decontaminate them has been shared widely on social media, but fact checkers are urging caution.  The Washington Post spoke to Benjamin Neuman, the chair of the Department of Biological Sciences at Texas A&M University, who suggested there was some evidence microwaves could kill some viruses in a lab setting, although scientists hadn’t verified whether the method would work for COVID-19. 
The Post suggested N95 surgical masks, which have a small metal plate attached, "absolutely cannot go in a microwave" and that other masks could be rendered ineffective by the heat of the microwave.
According to Snopes: "The [Centers for Disease Control and Prevention] has not explicitly forbidden the public from microwaving the face coverings nor weighed in on the effectiveness of the method. But it has made this recommendation, including in its April 9 guide: 'A washing machine should suffice in properly washing a face covering.'"
Meanwhile, Reuters found that microwaving face masks was a fire hazard, and local US fire authorities had publicly warned against the method. Image source: Facebook In an effort to curb the spread of misinformation, and in welcome news to inundated fact checkers everywhere, WhatsApp last week placed tighter limits on the forwarding of viral messages.
Where WhatsApp detects that a message has been forwarded more than usual — through a chain of at least five people — users will now be restricted to forwarding on that message to just one further chat. That may be a chat with one other person, or a group chat.
"We’ve seen a significant increase in the amount of forwarding which users have told us can feel overwhelming and can contribute to the spread of misinformation," the company, which is owned by Facebook, said in a statement.
The forwarding of these chain messages had previously been restricted to five chats since 2019. Given the extent of lockdown binge-viewing going on, it’s no surprise some people are having trouble separating fiction from reality. A photo shared more than 10,000 times on Facebook apparently shows four Italian healthcare workers collapsed on the floor of an operating theatre. The image is accompanied by a caption encouraging people to pray for Italy.
But, according to AFP Fact Check, the image isn’t from Italy — it’s a still taken from an episode of long-running US TV drama Grey’s Anatomy. Image source: Facebook #15:  Cocaine "We wouldn’t recommend trying a highly addictive drug in hopes of fighting off a viral disease. We rate this Pants on Fire!" - PolitiFact   We recently looked at a story where a man in the US died after consuming fish tank cleaner that contained a derivative of chloroquine, a substance President Donald Trump has touted as a potential cure for COVID-19.
The President isn’t the only one talking up the drug. Hydroxychloroquine, which is used mainly to treat malaria, has been championed by French media, celebrities such as Elon Musk, and conservative-leaning media including Breitbart.
But as the Washington Post Fact Checker explains in this video that tracks how misinformation about hydroxychloroquine was spread, scientists say there is only anecdotal evidence it is effective in treating COVID-19.  In a move to detect more coronavirus cases, the Victorian and South Australian governments this week announced they would begin testing anyone showing symptoms of COVID-19.
But how does Australia's overall testing compare to other countries?
This graph, prepared by Professor Mark Osborn of RMIT University, gives important context to the figures, combining the number of positive tests per 1000 conducted with the percentage of the population that has been tested.
Click through for a larger version.,
