https://pesacheck.org/false-headline-south-africa-has-not-developed-a-cure-for-covid-19-b64aa61db86a,Sign up Sign in Sign up Sign in PesaCheck Follow PesaCheck -- Listen Share An article claiming that South Africa has developed a cure for COVID-19 has a FALSE HEADLINE. The headline of the article, published by Opera News, says that South Africa has produced a cure for COVID-19, and that this cure would retail for less than 300 rand. However, there is no evidence that South Africa has developed a cure for COVID-19, and the text of the article appears to have been copied from an article published by Business Insider South Africa about a COVID-19 rapid antibody test that will cost less than 300 rand. Text from the Opera News article The Opera News article appears to have changed some words from the Business Insider article, possibly to avoid detection for plagiarism. Tarik Jasarevic, a spokesperson for the World Health Organization (WHO), told PesaCheck in a phone interview that to date there is no cure or vaccine for COVID-19. “What we have are several potential vaccines by different organizations from across the globe with a few of them on the human trial phases,” said Mr Jasarevic. WHO also says on its website that at the moment there is no specific treatment for the disease caused by a novel coronavirus, recommending that treatment be based on the patient’s clinical condition. The UN agency also stresses the need for supportive care for infected persons. While there is no cure for the disease, South Africa is the first country in Africa to take part in human clinical trials aimed at producing a potential vaccine against COVID-19. On June 23, the University of the Witwatersrand in Johannesburg announced the launch of the first clinical trial of a COVID-19 vaccine on the continent. The trial is being conducted in partnership with the Jenner Institute at the University of Oxford. The trial vaccine, known as ChAdOx1 nCoV-19, is already being tested in the UK and Brazil. On July 9, the Johannesburg-based University released a progress report on the ongoing clinical trial, which involves 2,000 volunteers aged 18–65, some of whom are HIV positive. The vaccine is now in Phase III clinical trials, which means researchers are assessing how well it works to prevent coronavirus infections across a broad range of ages. It will also evaluate the safety aspects of the vaccine and its ability to generate a good immune response. Researchers at Oxford University, who developed the vaccine, are also working with AstraZeneca on its further development and production. PesaCheck has looked into an article claiming that South Africa produced a cure for COVID-19 and finds that it has a FALSE HEADLINE. This post is part of an ongoing series of PesaCheck fact-checks examining content marked as potential misinformation on Facebook and other social media platforms. By partnering with Facebook and similar social media platforms, third-party fact-checking organisations like PesaCheck are helping to sort fact from fiction. We do this by giving the public deeper insight and context to posts they see in their social media feeds. Have you spotted what you think is fake news or false information on Facebook? Here’s how you can report. And, here’s more information on PesaCheck’s methodology for fact-checking questionable content. This fact-check was written by PesaCheck Fact-Checker James Okong’o and edited by PesaCheck Deputy Editor Enock Nyariki. The article was approved for publication by PesaCheck Managing Editor Eric Mugendi. PesaCheck is East Africa’s first public finance fact-checking initiative. It was co-founded by Catherine Gicheru and Justin Arenstein, and is being incubated by the continent’s largest civic technology and data journalism accelerator: Code for Africa. It seeks to help the public separate fact from fiction in public pronouncements about the numbers that shape our world, with a special emphasis on pronouncements about public finances th